<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-03-16T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-03-16T07:00:00-05:00" n="480" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d480">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">251.11 Insull, Samuel/366:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Greece</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Athens</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-03-16T14:00:00+02:00">March 16, 1934—2
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 16—9:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>33. The Foreign Minister informed me this morning that Insull left
                                Piraeus Wednesday<note n="35" xml:id="d480fn35">March 14.</note> at
                                4 p.m. for Port Said in small Greek freighter named <hi rend="italic">Maiotis</hi>, owner Symonyminos. Voyage will take
                                approximately 3 days and I have cabled particulars to Cairo in case
                                this information is correct. Meanwhile on the basis of your telegram
                                10, February 6, 5 p.m.,<note n="36" xml:id="d480fn36">Not
                                    printed.</note> I have told the Foreign Minister that my
                                Government does not desire to impede his flight into Egypt.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>